/src/ittf/jswizzi/level_0/step_1__copy/t/assignments.html.ittf

                            
    

   1 $group
   2     h3 Assignment operators
   3     $
   4         var atests = [];
   5         function at(label, result) {
   6             atests.push( { label: label,  result: result });)
   7         }
   8         var a = 0;
   9         at( 'var a = 0; a += 2' ,  a += 2 );)
  10         var a = 0;
  11         at( 'var a = 0; a -= 2' ,  a -= 2 );)
  12         var a = 3;
  13         at( 'var a = 3; a *= 2' ,  a *= 2 );)
  14         var a = 3;
  15         at( 'var a = 3; a /= 2' ,  a /= 2 );)
  16         var a = 3;
  17         at( 'var a = 3; a %= 2' ,  a %= 2 );)
  18         var a = 3;
  19         at( 'var a = 3; a <<= 2' ,  a <<= 2 );)
  20         var a = 3;
  21         at( 'var a = 3; a >>= 2' ,  a >>= 2 );)
  22         var a = 3;
  23         at( 'var a = 3; a >>>= 2' ,  a >>>= 2 );)
  24         var a = 3;
  25         at( 'var a = 3; a &= 2' ,  a &= 2 );)
  26         var a = 3;
  27         at( 'var a = 3; a |= 2' ,  a |= 2 );)
  28         var a = 3;
  29         at( 'var a = 3; a ^= 2' ,  a ^= 2 );)
  30     $foreach test in atests
  31         p ${test.label} = ${test.result}
  32     br
  33     br

/src/ittf/jswizzi/level_0/step_1__copy/t/expressions.html.ittf

                            
    

   1 $group
   2     h3 Unary expressions
   3     $
   4         var utests = [];
   5         function ut(label, result) {
   6             utests.push( { label: label,  result: result });)
   7         }
   8         ut( '+2' ,  +2 );)
   9         ut( '-2' ,  -2 );)
  10         ut( '!(2 == 2)' ,  !(2 == 2) );)
  11         ut( '~2' ,  ~2 );)
  12         var a = 0;
  13         ut ('a', 0)
  14         ut( '++a' ,  ++a );)
  15         ut( '--a' ,  --a );)
  16         ut( 'typeof 3' ,  typeof 3 );)
  17         var b = { id: 1 };
  18         //TODO ut( 'delete b.id' , delete b.id );
  19     $foreach test in utests
  20         p ${test.label} = ${test.result}
  21     br
  22     h4 Not implemented
  23     p void operator
  24     p void operator
  25     br
  26     br
  27     h3 Binary expressions
  28     $
  29         var tests = [];
  30         function t(label, result) {
  31             tests.push( { label: label,  result: result });)
  32         }
  33         t( '2 + 2' ,  2 + 2 );)
  34         t( '5 - 2' ,  5 - 2 );)
  35         t( '3 * 3' ,  3 * 3 );)
  36         t( '6 / 2' ,  6 / 2 );)
  37         t( '5 % 2' ,  5 % 2 );)
  38         t( '5 == 2' ,  5 == 2 );)
  39         t( '5 != 2' ,  5 != 2 );)
  40         t( '5 > 2' ,  5 > 2 );)
  41         t( '5 >= 5' ,  5 >= 5 );)
  42         t( '5 < 2' ,  5 < 2 );)
  43         t( '5 <= 5' ,  5 <= 5 );)
  44         t( '"a" in { a: 1}' ,  "a" in { a: 1} );)
  45         //TODO t( '5 instanceof String' , 5 instanceof String );
  46         t( 'String(5)' ,  String(5) );)
  47         t( 'Number(\'5.5\')' ,  Number('5.5') );)
  48         t( 'Date(2013, 6, 12)' ,  Date(2013, 6, 12) );)
  49         t( 'String(5) instanceof String' ,  String(5) instanceof String );)
  50         t( 'Number(\'5.5\') instanceof Number' ,  Number('5.5') instanceof Number );)
  51         t( 'Date(2013, 6, 12) instanceof Date' ,  Date(2013, 6, 12) instanceof Date );)
  52         t( '5 << 5' ,  5 << 5 );)
  53         t( '5 >> 5' ,  5 >> 5 );)
  54         t( '5 >>> 5' ,  5 >>> 5 );)
  55         t( '5 | 5' ,  5 | 5 );)

   5         var commands = [];

   7         for (var i=0; i<actions.length; i++) {
   8             var tokens = actions[i].trim().split(' ');
   9             var command = { name: tokens[0] };
  10             commands.push( command);)
  11         }

  13     div Let us inspect the 'commands' variable content.

  15         + Commands: ${ _.inspect(commands) }
  16     h4 Commands passed as mixin parameter
  17     p We perform a crazy operation, a template macro statement with
  18         + a multistatement jswizzi expression. We intersperse  command names
  19         + with dashes.
  20     $foreach command in commands
  21         div ${ command.name.toUpperCase()[0] + ' - ' + command.name }
  22         div This is quite crazy. But it works! -> ${ var len = command.name.length, output = ''; for (var i=0; i<len; i++) { output += command.name[i]; if (i < len -1) { output += ' - '}; _.log(output) } return output; }
  23     p That is why mTree stays for "magical tree".
  24     p See in wizzi-mtree/loader/ittfinterpolate.js how this works.

/src/ittf/languageschemas/css/level_0/step_1__copy/t/gridSystem_float.css.ittf

                            
    

   1 $group
   2     - thanks to http://j4n.co/blog/Creating-your-own-css-grid-system
   3     $
   4         var columns = 6
   5         var percWidth = 100
   6         var maxWidth = 1200
   7         var gutter = 12
   8     - The basic grid contains just a few elements
   9     - . container
  10     - . rows
  11     - . columns
  12     - . gutters (the space between columns)
  13     - The width of the container is generally 100%,
  14     - but you might want to set a max-width for larger displays.
  15     . gsf-grid-container
  16         width ${percWidth}%
  17         max-width ${maxWidth}px
  18     - Using the 'border-box' model, we can create gutters with ease.
  19     - setting border box on all elements inside the grid
  20     . gsf-grid-container *
  21         box-sizing border-box
  22     - cleafix hack -  to make sure everything inside
  23     - the row stays inside the row.
  24     . gsf-row:before
  25         + .gsf-row:after
  26         content ""
  27         display table
  28         clear both
  29     - To prevent that empty columns will stack on top of each other
  30     - we'll give our columns a min-height of 1px as well as float them.
  31     < [class*='gsf-col-']
  32         float left
  33         min-height 1px
  34         - our gutter
  35         padding ${gutter}px
  36     - To find the width of one column, all we have to do is divide
  37     - the total number of columns by the width of the container.
  38     - In our case, the width of the container is ${percWidth}%,
  39     - and we want ${columns} columns, so ${percWidth}/${columns} = ${percWidth/columns}%.
  40     < [class*='gsf-col-']
  41         width ${percWidth/columns}%
  42     $for var i=1; i<columns+1; i++
  43         . gsf-col-${i}
  44             width ${(percWidth/columns)*i}%
  45     $for var i=0; i<columns; i++
  46         . gsf-sm-${i}
  47             margin-left ${(percWidth/columns)*i}%
  48             $if i > 0
  49                 @ *margin-left ${(percWidth/columns)*i-0.005}%
  50     . gsf-outline
  51         + .gsf-outline *
  52         outline 1px solid #F6A1A1
  53     - some extra column content styling
  54     < [class*='gsf-col-'] > p
  55         background-color #FFC2C2
  56         padding 0
  57         margin 0
  58         text-align center
  59         color white

   1 $group

   1 $group

   3     # ========================================
   4     # EXCEPTIONS
   5     # ========================================
   6     +
   7     #
   8         # Try/catch
   9     var result = null
  10     try
  11         set result = 100
  12         var rnd = (int)(Math.random() * 99)
  13         if rnd % 2 == 0
  14             set result /= 0
  15         else
  16             set result /= 2
  17         _ sendResult
  18             @ result
  19     catch ex
  20         log ex.message
  21     finally
  22         set result = null
  23     #
  24         # Throw an exception
  25     function divide
  26         param a
  27         param b
  28         if b == 0
  29             throw
  30                 new Error
  31                     @ 'You are about to divide by 0'

  24                     times

  26                         _ getItems
  27                             . length

  29         # Building templates, various binary expressions can be
  30         # easer to code when written in indented form.
  31         #

  33         ||
  34             + seen_one
  35             _ getNext

  38                     + is_ok
  39                     _ checkName
  40                         @ name
  41     var r2
  42         &&
  43             + seen_one
  44             + seen_two
  45     #
  46         # Work in this way
  47         # or : ||
  48         # and : &&
  49         # equal strict : ===
  50         # notequal strict : !==
  51         # equal : ==
  52         # not equal : !=
  53         # minus : minus
  54         # plus : plus
  55         # times : times
  56         # divide : divide
  57         # power : power
  58         # mod : mod
  59         # xor : xor
  60         # xand : xand
  61         # gt : gt
  62         # ge : >=
  63         # lt : lt

/src/ittf/languageschemas/js/level_0/step_1__copy/t/iterations.js.ittf

                            
    

   1 $group
   2     +
   3     # ========================================
   4     # ITERATIONS
   5     # ========================================
   6     +
   7     #
   8         # The foreach iteration
   9     foreach item in arr5
  10         log 'item ', i, item
  11     #
  12         # The backeach iteration (foreach backwards)
  13     backeach item in arr5
  14         log 'item ', i, item
  15     #
  16         # Nested foreach
  17         # Until 6 nesting are allowed
  18         # The letters used for iterations are, in order:
  19         # i, j, k, l, m, n
  20     foreach item5 in arr5
  21         log 'item5', i, item5
  22         foreach item4 in arr4
  23             log 'item4', j, item4
  24     #
  25         # Nested backeach
  26         # Until 6 nesting are allowed
  27         # The letters used for iterations are in order:
  28         # i, j, k, l, m, n
  29     backeach item5 in arr5
  30         log 'item5', i, item5
  31         backeach item4 in arr4
  32             log 'item4', j, item4
  33     #
  34         # Foreach's and backeach's
  35         # can be mixed
  36     backeach item5 in arr5
  37         log 'item5', i, item5
  38         foreach item4 in arr4
  39             log 'item4', j, item4
  40     #
  41         # For loops
  42     for var k in object3
  43         log k, object3[k]
  44     #
  45         # While loops
  46     var parent = node.parent
  47     while typeof(parent) !== 'undefined'
  48         log parent.id
  49         set parent = parent.parent
  50     #
  51         # Inside iterations you can use break and continue nodes
  52     for var k in object3
  53         if k === 'go'
  54             break
  55         if k === 'skip'
  56             continue
  57         log k, object3[k]

  11     var object1_b = {}

  14     var object2

  16             @ name 'stefi'
  17             @ friends
  18                 [
  19                     {

  21                     {
  22                         @ name 'marilu'

  25     var object3
  26         {
  27             @ name 'stefi'
  28             { address
  29                 @ city 'Reggio nell'Emilia'
  30             [ friends
  31                 {
  32                     @ name 'arthur'
  33                 {
  34                     @ name 'marilu'
  35     #
  36         # How to declare an empty array
  37     var arr1
  38         [
  39     var arr1_b = []
  40     #
  41         # How to declare simple arrays
  42     var arr2
  43         [ 'stefi'

  45     var arr3
  46         [ 'stefi', 'annie'
  47     var arr3_b = [ 'stefi', 'annie' ]
  48     #
  49         # How to declare an array structure
  50     var arr4
  51         [
  52             @ 'stefi'
  53             @ 'annie'
  54     var arr5
  55         [
  56             {
  57                 @ id 1
  58             {
  59                 @ id 2

  61         # Object and array properties can be functions
  62         # or results of functions call.
  63         # Note: properties may be written both escaped or not.
  64     var object4
  65         {
  66             @ name
  67                 _ 'stefi'.toUpperCase()
  68             { address
  69                 @ city 'Reggio nell\'Emilia'
  70             { address2
  71                 @ city 'Reggio nell'Emilia'
  72             @ getInfo
  73                 function
  74                     return this.name + ', city: ' + this.address.city

/src/ittf/languageschemas/js/level_0/step_1__copy/basic.js.ittf

                            
    

   1 module
   2     kind jsfile
   3     $
   4         /* required by examples */
   5         var isUpperCaseRequired = false;
   6     #
   7         # Rationale
   8         #
   9         # Ittf documents are, at the same time, templates and lego brick pieces.
  10         # Every node of an ittf document is computable and composable.
  11         # It may contain, be the result of, be the starting point of, a computation
  12         # or a composition.
  13         # To 'alberize', render in indented tree format, a javascript
  14         # source code greatly simplifies the brick composition of a module,
  15         # at the cost of a little weird coding style that is easy to get
  16         # acquainted of.
  17         # The biggest cost, at the moment, is the lack of syntax highlighting and
  18         # code completion, but Wizzi studio is under way and it will
  19         # make up for that.
  20         #
  21     #
  22         # In many cases you can choose how much to 'alberize' a statement.
  23     # This statement ...
  24     var myLetters
  25         _ 'a, b, c'.split
  26             @ '.'
  27             ._ trim
  28                 ._ toUpperCase
  29     # ... can be written without indentation
  30     var myLetters = 'a, b, c'.split('.').trim().toUpperCase()
  31     # Sometimes it is a matter of style and personal preference.
  32     # Other times an indentation is required when templating. Imagine that upper case
  33     # be a design choice in differentent scenarios.
  34     # You could write ...
  35     var myLetters
  36         _ 'a, b, c'.split
  37             @ '.'
  38             ._ trim
  39                 $if isUpperCaseRequired
  40                     ._ toUpperCase
  41     # A deep indentation allow a template decision on every node
  42     # of the AST.
  43     $include declarations
  44     $include objects
  45     $include expressions
  46     $include conditionals
  47     $include iterations
  48     $include exceptions
  49     $include functions
  50     $include classes
  51     $include debug
  52     $include test

  21                 log 'Hii i am ' + this.name
  22         m create
  23             static
  24             string name
  25             { options
  26                 boolean canSpeakLikeAHuman
  27             return
  28                 new Horse
  29                     @ name
  30                     @ options

   1 module
   2     kind react
   3     #
   4         # React module kind
   5         #
   6         # The wizzi factory is language and framework agnostic.
   7         # It is a manipulator, transformer and composer of text documents,
   8         # to whose semantics it is indifferent.
   9         # The plugins are those that target specific domains.
  10         #
  11         # To came to life, and became an application, the wizzi factory
  12         # has chosen a few target domains, first of all: nodejs, javascript, html,
  13         # style sheets, and has implemented some core plugins, that are
  14         # the starters of the factory.
  15         #
  16         # A fundamental component of the wizzi factory application, which development
  17         # is under way, is the Wizzi studio web application. For the UI of
  18         # Wizzi studio the React framework has been chosen.
  19         #
  20         # The 'js' wizzi schema, implemented by the wizzi-js plugin, contains elements
  21         # taylored for the React framework.
  22         #
  23         #
  24         # This module kind supports the new javascript synthax and React jsx.
  25         # The generated source must be transpiled using Babel.
  26         #
  27     $include component
  28     $include container

   1 demo_module( mtree_composition,  0,  2 )
   2     #
   3         # DEMO: How to load a composed ittf document into an mTree.
   4         #
   5         # We use an `html` ittf document to show an example of
   6         # composition, calling mixins.
   7         #
   8         # The `html` artifact here is not generated.

/src/ittf/mtree/level_1/step_1__copy/treeview_1.html.ittf

                            
    

   1 html
   2     body
   3     $
   4         function buildNode(parent, childCount, deep) {
   5             parent.childs = [];
   6             if (deep > 3) { return; }
   7             parent.childs = [];
   8             for (var i = 0; i < childCount; i++) {
   9                 var child = { id: parent.id + '-' + i};
  10                 buildNode( child,  childCount,  deep + 1);)
  11                 parent.childs.push( child);)
  12             }
  13         }
  14         var tree = { id: 0 };
  15         buildNode( tree,  2,  0);)
  16     div Let us inspect the 'tree' variable we built.
  17     pre
  18         + tree: ${ _.inspect(tree) }
  19     # a brute force tree view rendering
  20     # working until 3 levels deep.
  21     ul
  22         $foreach node in tree.childs
  23             lia( node${node.id},  /node${node.id} )
  24                 $if node.childs.length > 0
  25                     ul
  26                         $foreach node2 in node.childs
  27                             lia( node${node2.id},  /node${node2.id} )
  28                                 $if node2.childs.length > 0
  29                                     ul
  30                                         $foreach node3 in node2.childs
  31                                             lia( node${node3.id},  /node${node3.id} )
  32     # beautifull tree view rendering
  33     # without depth limits
  34     $function nodeView
  35         $param parent
  36         div node${parent.id}
  37             $foreach nodeChild in parent.childs
  38                 $_ nodeView
  39                     $@ nodeChild
  40     $_ nodeView
  41         $@ tree

  33         # IRIs are a fundamental concept of Linked Data,

/src/ittf/plugin/examples/ittf__copy/xsd/xsd_structures.xsd.ittf

                            
    

   1 xsd
   2     xmlns xs http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema
   3     element-form-default qualified
   4     language EN
   5     target-namespace http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema
   6     version structures.xsd (wd-20091203)
   7     #
   8         # source http://www.w3.org/TR/2009/WD-xmlschema11-1-20091203/structures.html
   9     #
  10         # The simpleType element and all of its members are defined
  11         # in datatypes.xsd
  12     #
  13         # simple type for the value of the 'namespace' attr of
  14         # 'any' and 'anyAttribute'
  15     #
  16         # Value is
  17         # ##any      - - any non-conflicting WFXML/attribute at all
  18         # ##other    - - any non-conflicting WFXML/attribute from
  19         # namespace other than targetNS
  20         # ##local    - - any unqualified non-conflicting WFXML/attribute
  21         # one or     - - any non-conflicting WFXML/attribute from
  22         # more URI        the listed namespaces
  23         # references
  24         # (space separated)
  25         # ##targetNamespace or ##local may appear in the above list, to
  26         # refer to the targetNamespace of the enclosing
  27         # schema or an absent targetNamespace respectively
  28     #
  29         # notations for use within  schema documents
  30     #
  31         # In keeping with the XML Schema WG's standard versioning policy,
  32         # this schema document will persist at the URI
  33         # http://www.w3.org/2009/12/XMLSchema.xsd.
  34         # At the date of issue it can also be found at the URI
  35         # http://www.w3.org/2009/XMLSchema/XMLSchema.xsd.
  36         # The schema document at that URI may however change in the future,
  37         # in order to remain compatible with the latest version of XSD
  38         # and its namespace.  In other words, if XSD or the XML Schema
  39         # namespace change, the version of this document at
  40         # http://www.w3.org/2009/XMLSchema/XMLSchema.xsd will change accordingly;
  41         # the version at http://www.w3.org/2009/12/XMLSchema.xsd will not change.
  42         # Previous dated (and unchanging) versions of this schema document
  43         # include:
  44         # http://www.w3.org/2009/04/XMLSchema.xsd
  45         # (XSD 1.1 Candidate Recommendation)
  46         # http://www.w3.org/2004/10/XMLSchema.xsd
  47         # (XSD 1.0 Recommendation, Second Edition)
  48         # http://www.w3.org/2001/05/XMLSchema.xsd
  49         # (XSD 1.0 Recommendation, First Edition)
  50         #
  51     include datatypes.xsd
  52     import http://www.w3.org/2001/xml.xsd
  53         namespace http://www.w3.org/XML/1998/namespace
  54         #
  55             # Get access to the xml: attribute groups for xml:lang
  56             # as declared on 'schema' and 'documentation' below
  57             #

/src/ittf/plugin/examples/t/load_wizzimodel.js.ittf

                            
    

   1 $group
   2     $params functionName, schemaName, modelName
   3     function ${functionName}
   4         # Create a filesystem factory without access control
   5         # requiring the local plugin.
   6         _ wizzi.fsnoaclFactory
   7             @ wizziFactoryConfig
   8             f_cb_throw( wf )
   9                 # Now we can load the model
  10                 _ wf.loadModel
  11                     _ path.join
  12                         @ __dirname
  13                         @ 'ittf'
  14                         @ '${schemaName}'
  15                         @ '${modelName}.${schemaName}.ittf'
  16                     {
  17                     f_cb_throw( wizziModel )
  18                         # And print the wizzi model object
  19                         _ wizzi.file.write
  20                             _ path.join
  21                                 @ __dirname
  22                                 @ 'output'
  23                                 @ '${modelName}.${schemaName}.json'
  24                             _ stringify
  25                                 @ wizziModel.toJson()
  26                                 @ null
  27                                 @ 2

                        

                    

                    

                        

                            
/src/ittf/plugin/examples/t/loadModel.js.ittf

                            
    

   1 $group
   2     $params step, ittfDocumentName, commandLine|@@null
   3     $
   4         var saveJson = false;
   5         var printJson = false;
   6         var printModel = false;
   7         var printDashes = false;
   8         if (commandLine !== null) {
   9             var commands = commandLine.split(';')
  10             for (var i=0; i<commands.length; i++) {
  11                 var tokens = commands[i].trim().split(':');
  12                 if (tokens.length == 2) {
  13                     if (tokens[0] == 'print') {
  14                         var actions = tokens[1].trim().split(' ');
  15                         for (var j=0; j<actions.length; j++) {
  16                             if (actions[j] === 'json') {
  17                                 printJson = true;
  18                             }
  19                             if (actions[j] === 'model') {
  20                                 printModel = true;
  21                             }
  22                             if (actions[j] === 'dashes') {
  23                                 printDashes = true;
  24                             }
  25                         }
  26                     }
  27                 }
  28                 if (tokens.length == 1) {
  29                     if (tokens[0] === 'save') {
  30                         saveJson = true;
  31                     }
  32                 }
  33             }
  34         }
  35     # Create a filesystem factory without access control
  36     _ wizzi.fsnoaclFactory
  37         {
  38             @ plugins
  39                 {
  40                     @ items
  41                         [
  42                             @ 'wizzi-core'
  43                             @ 'v4-wizzi-js'
  44                             @ 'wizzi-html'
  45                             @ 'wizzi-docs'
  46                             @ './plugin/local/index'
  47                     @ basePluginsFolder
  48                         _ path.resolve
  49                             @ __dirname
  50                             @ '..'
  51                             @ '..'
  52                             @ '..'
  53         f_cb_throw( wf )
  54             # Now we can load the model
  55             _ wf.loadModel
  56                 _ path.join
  57                     @ __dirname
  58                     @ 'step_${step}'

/src/ittf/plugin/source/ittf__copy/lib/artifacts/demo/jsonld/gen/main.js.ittf

                            
    

   1 module wizzi-demo.plugin.lib.artifacts.demo.jsonlg.gen.main
   2     kind jsfile
   3     # Example of language artifact that targets
   4     # the JSON-LG 1.0 (2014) specification.
   5     #
   6     # This is a code write based artifact generator.
   7     # It generates a json document.
   8     #
   9     var md = module.exports = {}
  10     var myname = 'wizzi-demo.plugins.lib.artifacts.demo.jsonlg.main';
  11     set md.gen
  12         function gen
  13             { model
  14             { ctx
  15             callback
  16             # check the model is a wizzi model of type 'demo'
  17             if model.wzElement !== 'demo'
  18                 return
  19                     _ callback
  20                         _ ctx.error
  21                             @ myname + " error: the model paramater should be an 'demo' wizzi model"
  22                             @ model
  23             _ genItem(model, ctx)
  24             _ callback(null, ctx)
  25     function genItem
  26         param item
  27         param ctx
  28         var st = specialTags[item.wzElement]
  29         if st
  30             return
  31                 _ st(item, ctx)
  32         _ ctx.write('<' + item.wzTag)
  33         _ genAttrs(item, ctx)
  34         if item.items.length > 0
  35             _ ctx.w('>')
  36             if item.wzName && item.wzName.length > 0
  37                 _ ctx.write(item.wzName)
  38             _ genItems(item.items, ctx, { indent: true })
  39             _ ctx.w('</' + item.wzTag + '>')
  40         else
  41             _ ctx.w('>' + (item.wzName && item.wzName.length > 0 ? item.wzName : '') + '</' + item.wzTag + '>')
  42     function genItems
  43         param items
  44         param ctx
  45         param options
  46         if options && options.indent
  47             _ ctx.indent()
  48         foreach item in items
  49             _ genItem(item, ctx)
  50         if options && options.indent
  51             _ ctx.deindent()
  52     function genAttrs
  53         param item
  54         param ctx
  55         foreach a in item.getAttributes()
  56             _ ctx.write
  57                 @ ' ' + a.name + '="' + a.value + '"'
  58         var styles = item.getStyleAttributes()
  59         if styles.length > 0
  60             var sb = []
  61             foreach style in styles
  62                 _ sb.push
  63                     @ style.name + ':' + style.value + ';'
  64             _ ctx.write
  65                 @ ' style="' + sb.join('') + '"'
  66     var specialTags = {}
  67     set specialTags.svg
  68         function
  69             param item
  70             param ctx
  71             _ ctx.w('<?xml version="1.0"?>')
  72             _ ctx.write('<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"')
  73             _ genAttrs(item, ctx)
  74             _ ctx.w('>')
  75             _ genItems(item.items, ctx, { indent: true })
  76             _ ctx.w('</svg>')
  77     set specialTags.linearGradient
  78         function
  79             param item
  80             param ctx
  81             _ ctx.write('<linearGradient')
  82             _ genAttrs(item, ctx)
  83             _ ctx.w('>')
  84             # TODO
  85             _ ctx.w('</linearGradient>')

/src/ittf/t/demo_prints.js.ittf

                            
    

   1 $group
   2     $params name, level|0, step|1
   3     function heading1
   4         param text
   5         log ''
   6         log '*'.repeat(120)
   7         log '** level ${level} - step ${step} - ${name} - ' + text
   8         log '*'.repeat(120)
   9         log ''
  10     function heading2
  11         param text
  12         log ''
  13         log '   ', '-'.repeat(100)
  14         log '   ','-- ${name} - ' + text
  15         log '   ', '-'.repeat(100)
  16         log ''
  17     function printArray
  18         param name
  19         param arr
  20         param fields
  21         param format
  22         if format === 'dashes'
  23             log '   ', '-'.repeat(100)
  24         log '   ', '* array ' + name + ' : '
  25         foreach item in arr
  26             log '    {', i
  27             var keys = fields || Object.keys(item)
  28             foreach k in keys
  29                 _ printValue
  30                     @ k
  31                     @ item[k]
  32     function printValue
  33         param k
  34         param v
  35         param format
  36         if format === 'dashes'
  37             log '   ', '-'.repeat(100)
  38         if verify.isNotEmpty(v)
  39             var lines
  40                 _ verify.splitLines
  41                     @ v
  42                     {
  43                         @ numbered true
  44             if lines.length === 1
  45                 log '   ', k, ':', lines[0].text
  46             else
  47                 for var i=0; i<lines.length; i++
  48                     if i === 0
  49                         log '   ', k, ':', lines[0].numFmt, lines[0].text
  50                     else
  51                         log '   ', spaces(k.length+1), ' ', lines[i].numFmt, lines[i].text
  52         elif verify.isObject(v)
  53             log '   ', k, ':', inspect(v)
  54         else
  55             log '   ', k, ':', v
  56     function spaces
  57         param len
  58         return new Array(len).join(' ')

/src/ittf/wizzijob/level_1/step_1__copy/ittf/lib/wizzi/schemas/model1.wfschema.ittf

                            
    

   1 wfschema model1
   2     #
   3     # The 'model1' schema defines a simple tree structure.
   4     # It has 2 elements:
   5     # . 'model1', the root.
   6     # . 'item', the node.
   7     # Both may contain children 'item' elements.
   8     # Every element has a name (the ittf node value).
   9     # 'item' elements have an 'order' attribute of type integer.
  10     #
  11     # In the generated javascript classes each element will have the properties:
  12     # . wzParent
  13     # . wzElement (the name of the schema element: 'model1' or 'item')
  14     # . wzTag (the ittf node name, in this case it will be equal to the wzElement property)
  15     # . wzName (the ittf node value)
  16     # . wzSourceLine (the file, row, col position of the element in the source ittf document)
  17     #
  18     # The 'item' element will have also the property
  19     # . order
  20     #
  21     e model1
  22         is-root
  23         r item/s
  24     e item
  25         a order
  26             type integer
  27         r item/s

  49         # before loading it in a wizzi model.
  50         # Using the model sample.docs.ittf as model context
  51         artifact basic with model ittf document
  52             src basic.withmodel.ittf
  53             schema ittf
  54             generator ittf/document
  55             extension ittf
  56             model-ref wf
  57                 export-name wf
  58     production
  59         dest-folder ${dest_folder}
  60         line-ref one
  61         line-ref two
  62         line-ref three

  11         cwd-folder ${ittf_lib_folder}

  13         # The synthax rules for xml ittf documents are here: TODO
  14         artifact basic no model xml document
  15             src basic.nomodel.xml.ittf
  16             schema xml
  17             generator xml/document
  18             extension xml
  19     line two
  20         cwd-folder ${models_folder}
  21         # Generates the json reprentation of a wizzi model
  22         # from a `demo` wizzi model (schema `demo`)
  23         # We can do this because the `demo` wizzi schema
  24         # declares the element:
  25         # export-to json
  26         artifact json dump of model wf.demo.ittf
  27             src wf.demo.ittf
  28             schema demo
  29             generator json/export
  30             dest-path wf.demo.export.json
  31             extension json
  32         # Regenerates the ittf of the loaded mTree (schema ittf).
  33         # This make sense when we have to preprocess, compose from various
  34         # documents or compose programmatically, an ittf document,
  35         # before loading it in a wizzi model.
  36         artifact ittf document of model wf.demo.ittf
  37             src wf.demo.ittf
  38             schema ittf
  39             generator ittf/document
  40             dest-path wf.demo.export.ittf
  41             extension ittf
  42     line three
  43         cwd-folder ${ittf_lib_folder}
  44         # Generates a xml document (pseudo schema xml)
  45         # Using the model wf.demo.ittf as model context
  46         # The synthax rules for xml ittf documents are here: TODO
  47         artifact basic with model xml document
  48             src basic.withmodel.xml.ittf
  49             schema xml
  50             generator xml/document
  51             extension xml
  52             model-ref wf
  53                 export-name wf
  54     production
  55         dest-folder ${dest_folder}
  56         line-ref one
  57         line-ref two

   1 demo_module( wizzi_job_mongodb_level_0_step_1_exec )
   2     var testMongodbUri = 'mongodb://localhost:27017/test'
   3     var testMongodbBaseFolder = 'c:/wizzifactory/users'
   4     _ wizzi.executeWizziJob
   5         {
   6             @ user 'stefi'
   7             @ role 'admin'
   8             @ storeKind 'mongodb'
   9             @ config
  10                 {
  11                     @ wfBaseFolder testMongodbBaseFolder
  12                     @ storeUri testMongodbUri
  13                     @ storeBaseFolder testMongodbBaseFolder
  14                     @ plugins
  15                         [
  16                             @ 'wizzi-core'
  17                             @ 'v4-wizzi-js'
  18                             @ 'wizzi-html'
  19                             @ 'wizzi-docs'
  20             @ job
  21                 {
  22                     @ name 'mongodb.level_0.step_1'
  23                     @ ittfDocumentUri
  24                         _ path.join
  25                             @ 'db://stefi/demo/wizzijob'
  26                             @ 'level_0'
  27                             @ 'step_1'
  28                             @ 'step_1.wfjob.ittf'
  29                     @ productionOptions
  30                         _ wizzi.productionOptions
  31                             {
  32                                 @ indentSpaces 4
  33                                 @ basedir __dirname
  34                                 @ verbose 2
  35                     @ globalContext
  36                         {
  37         function
  38             param err
  39             if err
  40                 log "Error executing wizzi instance job", err
  41             log 'Wizzi instance job mongodb.level_0.step_1 SUCCESSFULLY executed'

/src/ittf/wizzischema/level_0/step_1__copy/sample_0_1.wfschema.ittf

                            
    

   1 wfschema sample_0_1
   2     # Wizzi schema: sample_0_1
   3     #
   4     # Our first schema has a `root` and a single `element`
   5     # that could represent a product record information.
   6     #
   7     # Example
   8     #
   9     # sample_0_1
  10     #
  11     # item AlphaCPU 365
  12     # id 3789
  13     # category hw
  14     # price 140
  15     #
  16     # item BetaCPU 528
  17     # id 3891
  18     # category hw
  19     # price 270
  20     #
  21     e sample_0_1
  22         # This is the `root element`.
  23         # Its a good practice to give to the `root element`
  24         # the same name of the `schema`.
  25         is-root
  26         a currency
  27             # The currency `attribute` can be used to declare
  28             # the currency of price values. The default is dollar and
  29             # is restricted to dollars and euros.
  30             default
  31             restrict
  32                 enum
  33                     # dollar
  34                 enum â‚¬
  35                     # euro
  36         r productItem/s
  37             # The `root element` may contain productItem elements.
  38             # The relation `one-to-many` is the default.
  39             # The cardinality always is: `one-to-zero-or-many`.
  40             # The other possible relation is `one-to-one` (must be declared).
  41             # Example:
  42             # r productItem
  43             # one-to-one
  44             # In the generated javascript class of the `root element` this
  45             # declaration will produce the collection property: productItems.
  46             #
  47     e productItem
  48         # The product item `element`.
  49         # The `ittf node value` will contain the product name.
  50         # This must be said in the `element` comment in this way:
  51         # `The wzName is the product name.`
  52         # `wzName` is the name of the `ittf node value` property
  53         # in the generated javascript class that rapresent an `element`.
  54         tag item
  55         # The default `ittf node tag` of an `element` is its name, but is can
  56         # be changed declaring a `tag` `attribute.
  57         # Example of a productItem:
  58         #
  59         # item AlphaCPU 365
  60         # id 3789
  61         # category hw
  62         # price 140
  63         #
  64         a id
  65             # The product id (of type integer).
  66             # The other types are: string (default), boolean, float, date.
  67             type integer
  68         a category
  69             # The product category, that is restricted to
  70             # hardware or software items.
  71             restrict
  72                 enum sw
  73                     # software product
  74                 enum hw
  75                     # hardware product
  76         a price
  77             # The item price (of type float). The currency is declared in
  78             # the `root node`.
  79             type float

/src/ittf/wizzischema/level_0/step_2__copy/sample_0_2.wfschema.ittf

                            
    

   1 wfschema sample_0_2
   2     # Wizzi schema: sample_0_2
   3     #
   4     # In this second schema we implement a very common pattern
   5     # used mainly in language schemas: a tree node structure
   6     # without depth limits. Each node may have comments,
   7     # free attributes and sub nodes.
   8     #
   9     # Example
  10     #
  11     # sample_0_2
  12     #
  13     # < alfa
  14     # # An alfa node for ...
  15     # @ id 1
  16     # < beta
  17     # @ size 5
  18     # < gamma
  19     # @ id 3
  20     # < sigma
  21     # @ height 4
  22     # < tau
  23     # @ id 5
  24     # < delta
  25     # @ id 6
  26     #
  27     e comment
  28         # The comment `element`.
  29         # The `wzName` will contain a comment line.
  30         tag #
  31     e attribute
  32         # The attribute `element`.
  33         # The attribute name is free.
  34         # The `wzName` will contain a blank separated name value pair.
  35         tag @
  36     e node
  37         # The node `element`.
  38         # We declare a node `element` that may contain many
  39         # node elements in a relation `one-to-many` (default).
  40         # So any node may contain nodes without depth limits.
  41         tag <
  42         r comment/s
  43             # Node comment lines. Relation `one-to-many` (default)
  44         r attribute/s
  45             # Node attributes. Relation `one-to-many` (default)
  46         r node/s
  47             # Node sub nodes. Relation `one-to-many` (default)
  48     e sample_0_2 : node
  49         # The `root node` is derived from the node `element`.
  50         # So the root too may contain comments, attributes and sub nodes.
  51         is-root

                        

                    

                    

                        

                            
/src/ittf/wizzischema/level_0/step_3__copy/t/dtype.wfschema.ittf

                            
    

   1 $group
   2     $params type, format|@@null
   3     $
   4         var typeName = format ? format : type;
   5     e ${typeName} : datatype
   6         $hook
   7         $if type === 'string'
   8             $include verify_string
   9         $if type === 'object'
  10             $include verify_object
  11         $if type === 'array'
  12             $include verify_array
  13         $if type === 'integer' || type === 'number'
  14             $include verify_num
  15         m wminitialize
  16             set this.type = '${type}'
  17             $if format != null
  18                 set this.format = '${format}'
  19             $hook wminitialize

  94     # Discriminator
  95     # To help API consumers detect the object type,
  96     # you can add the discriminator/property-name keyword to model definitions.
  97     # This keyword points to the property that specifies the data type name:
  98     schema

 100             type-ref simpleObject
 101             type-ref components/schemas/complexObject

 103             property-name objectType
 104     schema simpleObject
 105         {
 106             string objectType
 107                 required
 108     schema complexObject
 109         {
 110             string objectType
 111                 required
 112     # The discriminator is used with any-of or one-of keywords only.
 113     # It is important that all the models mentioned below
 114     # any-of or one-of contain the property that the discriminator specifies.
 115     # This means, for example, that in our code above,
 116     # both simpleObject and complexObject must have the objectType property.
 117     # This property is required in these schemas
 118     # The discriminator keyword can be used by various API consumers.
 119     # One possible example are code generation tools: they can use
 120     # discriminator to generate program statements that typecast
 121     # request data to appropriate object type based
 122     # on the discriminator property value.
 123     # Mapping Type Names
 124     # It is implied, that the property to which discriminator refers,
 125     # contains the name of the target schema.
 126     # In the example above, the objectType property should contain either
 127     # simpleObject, or complexObject string.
 128     # If the property values do not match the schema names,
 129     # you can map the values to the names.
 130     # To do this, use the discriminator/mapping keyword:
 131     schema
 132         one-of
 133             type-ref Object1
 134             type-ref Object2
 135             type-ref sysObject.json#/sysObject
 136         discriminator
 137             property-name objectType
 138             map obj1 Object1
 139             map obj2 Object2
 140             map system sysObject.json#/sysObject
 141     schema Object1
 142         {
 143             string objectType
 144                 required
 145     schema Object2
 146         {
 147             string objectType
 148                 required

  26             # List of named schema object.
  27     e schemaObject : commentable
  28         # From Swagger definition

  30         # These types can be objects, but also primitives and arrays.`
  31         #
  32         # The `wzName` contains the name of the schemaObject.
  33         tag schema
  34         r datatype
  35             # A schemaObject is composed by one datatype, typically
  36             # an object or an array.
  37             one-to-one
  38         r discriminator
  39             # When the schema datatype is a combinator
  40             # element (oneOf, allOf, anyOf )
  41             # The discriminator points to the property that specifies
  42             # the data type name.
  43             one-to-one
  44     e datatype : commentable
  45         # An abstract element from which all datatypes are derived.
  46         # Derived elements, when their parent element is an object
  47         # datatype, are object properties, and the `wzName` contains
  48         # the property name.
  49         # When a property is part of an enum element
  50         # the `wzName` contains a blank separated name value pair and
  51         # the value string must be converteable to the type.
  52         is-abstract

  56         a_flag( writeOnly )

  60             one-to-one

  78             one-to-one

   1 $group
   2     $params step, schema, model
   3     # Create a filesystem factory without access control,
   4     # requiring the core wizzi plugins and other plugins used by generators.
   5     _ wizzi.fsnoaclFactory
   6         {
   7             @ plugins
   8                 {
   9                     @ items
  10                         [
  11                             @ 'wizzi-core'
  12                             @ 'wizzi-meta'
  13                             @ 'v4-wizzi-js'
  14                             @ 'v4-wizzi-html'

  18                             @ __dirname

  20             # Now we can generate the wizzi schema model types.
  21             # They will be written in the folder passed as second parameter.
  22             _ wf.generateModelTypes
  23                 _ path.join
  24                     @ __dirname
  25                     @ 'step_${step}'

  28                     @ __dirname
  29                     @ 'local'

  32                 f_cb_throw( result )

  40                         f_cb_throw( wizziModel )
  41                             if wizziModel.toJson
  42                                 _ printValue

   1 wfjob demo
   2     $
   3         var ittf_meta_folder      = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'meta');
   4         var ittf_root             = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'root');
   5         var ittf_mtree            = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'mtree');
   6         var ittf_jswizzi          = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'jswizzi');
   7         var ittf_wizzimodel       = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'wizzimodel');
   8         var ittf_wizzischema      = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'wizzischema');
   9         var ittf_languageschemas  = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'languageschemas');
  10         var ittf_wizzijob         = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'wizzijob');
  11         var ittf_plugin_source    = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'plugin', 'source');
  12         var ittf_plugin_examples  = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'plugin', 'examples');
  13         var ittf_tests            = path.join(__dirname, 'ittf', 'tests');
  14         var dest_folder           = path.join(__dirname, '..', 'dist');
  15     model meta
  16         schema json
  17         src ${ittf_meta_folder}/index.json.ittf
  18     line ittf-root
  19         cwd-folder ${ittf_root}
  20         dest-folder ${dest_folder}
  21         wfjob/any_js()
  22             ignore ${ittf_root}/**/*__copy.*/**/*.js.ittf
  23         wfjob/any_json()
  24             model-ref meta
  25                 export-name wfpackage
  26         wfjob/any_md()
  27             model-ref meta
  28                 export-name wfpackage

  31         dest-folder ${dest_folder}/mtree

  33             ignore ${ittf_mtree}/**/*__copy/**/*.js.ittf

  35             src ${ittf_mtree}/**/*__copy/**/*.ittf
  36             extension ittf
  37         $include wfjob/any_md
